1
00:00:01,040 --> 00:00:03,195
Let's formalize how

2
00:00:03,195 --> 00:00:05,760
a reinforcement learning
algorithm picks actions.

3
00:00:05,760 --> 00:00:08,010
In this video, you'll
learn about what is

4
00:00:08,010 --> 00:00:11,040
a policy in reinforcement
learning algorithm.

5
00:00:11,040 --> 00:00:12,195
Let's take a look.

6
00:00:12,195 --> 00:00:15,780
As we've seen, there are
many different ways that you

7
00:00:15,780 --> 00:00:19,020
can take actions in the
reinforcement learning problem.

8
00:00:19,020 --> 00:00:21,990
For example, we could decide

9
00:00:21,990 --> 00:00:25,605
to always go for
the nearer reward,

10
00:00:25,605 --> 00:00:29,070
so you go left if this
leftmost reward is

11
00:00:29,070 --> 00:00:33,250
nearer or go right if this
rightmost reward is nearer.

12
00:00:33,250 --> 00:00:37,490
Another way we could choose
actions is to always go for

13
00:00:37,490 --> 00:00:40,229
the larger reward or

14
00:00:40,229 --> 00:00:43,470
we could always go
for smaller reward,

15
00:00:43,470 --> 00:00:44,945
doesn't seem like a good idea,

16
00:00:44,945 --> 00:00:46,585
but it is another option,

17
00:00:46,585 --> 00:00:49,160
or you could choose to go left

18
00:00:49,160 --> 00:00:52,730
unless you're just one step
away from the lesser reward,

19
00:00:52,730 --> 00:00:54,905
in which case, you
go for that one.

20
00:00:54,905 --> 00:00:59,765
In reinforcement learning,
our goal is to come up with

21
00:00:59,765 --> 00:01:05,059
a function which is
called a policy Pi,

22
00:01:05,059 --> 00:01:08,165
whose job it is to take as input

23
00:01:08,165 --> 00:01:11,345
any state s and map it

24
00:01:11,345 --> 00:01:15,545
to some action a that
it wants us to take.

25
00:01:15,545 --> 00:01:19,745
For example, for this
policy here at the bottom,

26
00:01:19,745 --> 00:01:23,615
this policy would say that
if you're in state 2,

27
00:01:23,615 --> 00:01:27,230
then it maps us to
the left action.

28
00:01:27,230 --> 00:01:28,970
If you're in state 3,

29
00:01:28,970 --> 00:01:30,710
the policy says go left.

30
00:01:30,710 --> 00:01:33,450
If you are in state 4 also go

31
00:01:33,450 --> 00:01:38,145
left and if you're in
state 5, go right.

32
00:01:38,145 --> 00:01:40,805
Pi applied to state S,

33
00:01:40,805 --> 00:01:44,905
tells us what action it wants
us to take in that state.

34
00:01:44,905 --> 00:01:51,155
The goal of reinforcement
learning is to find a policy Pi

35
00:01:51,155 --> 00:01:53,810
or Pi of S that tells
you what action to

36
00:01:53,810 --> 00:01:57,175
take in every state so as
to maximize the return.

37
00:01:57,175 --> 00:02:00,260
By the way, I don't
know if policy is

38
00:02:00,260 --> 00:02:04,430
the most descriptive
term of what pi is,

39
00:02:04,430 --> 00:02:06,170
but it's one of
those terms that's

40
00:02:06,170 --> 00:02:08,255
become standard in
reinforcement learning.

41
00:02:08,255 --> 00:02:09,740
Maybe calling Pi a

42
00:02:09,740 --> 00:02:12,350
controller rather than
a policy would be

43
00:02:12,350 --> 00:02:15,450
more natural
terminology but policy

44
00:02:15,450 --> 00:02:16,830
is what everyone in

45
00:02:16,830 --> 00:02:19,105
reinforcement learning
now calls this.

46
00:02:19,105 --> 00:02:20,960
In the last video, we've gone

47
00:02:20,960 --> 00:02:22,670
through quite a few concepts in

48
00:02:22,670 --> 00:02:26,330
reinforcement learning from
states to actions to reward,

49
00:02:26,330 --> 00:02:28,145
to returns, to policies.

50
00:02:28,145 --> 00:02:29,870
Let's do a quick
review of them in

51
00:02:29,870 --> 00:02:31,700
the next video and
then we'll go on to

52
00:02:31,700 --> 00:02:35,625
start developing algorithms
for finding that policies.

